1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:01,480
When you encode text into binary

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:04,200
it's often nice to use as little data as possible

3
00:00:04,720 --> 00:00:10,600
So you might naturally wonder: is there some kind of fundamental limit on how efficiently text can be compressed

4
00:00:11,520 --> 00:00:14,120
The default encoding with ASCII is pretty inefficient

5
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:16,920
Each character is represented with eight full bits

6
00:00:17,360 --> 00:00:18,440
If you apply a little cleverness

7
00:00:18,880 --> 00:00:21,400
associating more common characters with smaller bitstrings

8
00:00:22,240 --> 00:00:24,840
you can get this down to an average of around four bits per character

9
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:27,240
And then much smarter methods than that

10
00:00:27,440 --> 00:00:29,800
that leverage patterns among long sequences of text

11
00:00:30,240 --> 00:00:31,320
can get even better still

12
00:00:32,080 --> 00:00:32,360
But again

13
00:00:32,800 --> 00:00:33,320
what's the limit

14
00:00:34,240 --> 00:00:36,520
I'm guessing many of you might have heard an estimate here

15
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:37,880
I will share one at the end

16
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:43,920
But much more interesting than any single numerical answer is how you would even approach answering it

17
00:00:44,320 --> 00:00:46,200
This question dates back at least the 1940s

18
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:50,040
with Claude Shannon's seminal work that kicked off information theory

19
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:58,840
Now what's very interesting is how the math that he developed to answer questions like this has turned out to be surprisingly useful for modern machine learning

20
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:01,240
To take the salient example of today

21
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:03,320
when large language models are trained

22
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:08,920
the pre-training portion of that is usually described as being about next-token prediction

23
00:01:09,440 --> 00:01:11,960
specifically using something called cross-entropy loss

24
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:13,080
Now that term

25
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:13,480
cross-entropy

26
00:01:14,160 --> 00:01:15,560
has its roots in information theory

27
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:23,080
But what's also interesting is that one of the conclusions of information theory says that prediction and compression are mathematically equivalent

28
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:25,720
They turn out to be two sides of the same coin

29
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:33,320
which means you can entirely reframe how you think about the pre-training objective as not really being about next-token prediction per se

30
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:37,800
but instead as being about creating the most efficient possible text compressor

31
00:01:38,480 --> 00:01:38,680
Later

32
00:01:38,720 --> 00:01:40,200
I'll explain exactly how that works

33
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:41,160
But when you do

34
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:46,400
I think it offers more clarity on what this notion of cross-entropy really is and why you're using it

35
00:01:46,720 --> 00:01:46,920
Also

36
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:47,760
I don't know about you

37
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:48,520
but to me at least

38
00:01:48,640 --> 00:01:54,520
there's just something very intriguing about using compression as a fundamental objective while pursuing intelligence

39
00:01:55,520 --> 00:01:55,800
In fact

40
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,160
some people have gone so far as to say compression is intelligence

